00:47:24.610 --> 00:47:26.860
have all of these
embassies there where

00:47:26.860 --> 00:47:29.660
they have a staff that wants
to eat the kind of specialties

00:47:29.660 --> 00:47:30.930
from their home country.

00:47:30.930 --> 00:47:35.840
So nearly every nationality
in West Africa at least

00:47:35.840 --> 00:47:37.704
is represented by restaurant.

00:47:37.704 --> 00:47:39.120
We have a lot of
restaurants here,

00:47:39.120 --> 00:47:42.010
but they tend to come
from certain countries.

00:47:42.010 --> 00:47:46.390
Not all of them, but I love
going down to DC and eating.

00:47:46.390 --> 00:47:47.610
And I love Ben's Chili Bowl.

00:47:47.610 --> 00:47:48.151
Who wouldn't?

00:47:48.151 --> 00:47:50.760
I wish we had it here.

00:47:50.760 --> 00:47:51.260
Thank you.

00:47:51.260 --> 00:47:52.246
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:47:52.246 --> 00:47:54.509
AUDIENCE: I'm from the
suburbs in the Midwest,

00:47:54.509 --> 00:47:56.550
and it was a big deal when
we got our first sushi

00:47:56.550 --> 00:47:57.810
restaurant in 2005.

00:47:57.810 --> 00:47:58.665
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:58.665 --> 00:48:00.373
ROBERT SIETSEMA: What
kind of restaurant?

00:48:00.373 --> 00:48:01.640
AUDIENCE: A sushi restaurant.

00:48:01.640 --> 00:48:03.848
ROBERT SIETSEMA: And how
far were you from the ocean?

00:48:03.848 --> 00:48:05.590
AUDIENCE: Oh, I'm
from Illinois, so we

00:48:05.590 --> 00:48:07.200
were close to Lake Michigan.

00:48:07.200 --> 00:48:08.840
Could you talk a
little about what

00:48:08.840 --> 00:48:13.450
it takes for foods that start
off more specialized to go

00:48:13.450 --> 00:48:14.120
mainstream?

00:48:14.120 --> 00:48:17.535
And what kind of foods you
think now are up and coming?

00:48:17.535 --> 00:48:19.160
ROBERT SIETSEMA:
That's great question.

00:48:19.160 --> 00:48:23.050
And it used to be that you would
be kind of afraid to eat sushi

00:48:23.050 --> 00:48:25.280
if you were more than
50 miles from the shore.

00:48:25.280 --> 00:48:27.860
But it's Japanese
food is something

00:48:27.860 --> 00:48:30.680
that has become
tremendously popularized.

00:48:30.680 --> 00:48:34.410
It probably started with
the Japanese miracle, which

00:48:34.410 --> 00:48:36.660
was pretty much in
the '70s and '80s,

00:48:36.660 --> 00:48:39.760
whereby Japan
finally shrugged off

00:48:39.760 --> 00:48:47.840
their inferiority economically
and became a powerhouse.

00:48:47.840 --> 00:48:50.260
They've since dropped
from that position.

00:48:50.260 --> 00:48:52.820
But the fact that they were
Japanese business people

00:48:52.820 --> 00:48:57.430
running all over the country and
representing Japanese companies

00:48:57.430 --> 00:49:00.550
meant that they wanted
to have food from home.

00:49:00.550 --> 00:49:03.780
And at that time around
Grand Central Station,

00:49:03.780 --> 00:49:06.950
we had restaurants
that served fugu,

00:49:06.950 --> 00:49:10.220
for God's sake, and
eels, and okonomiyaki,

00:49:10.220 --> 00:49:14.240
and things that specialized
in very particular forms

00:49:14.240 --> 00:49:15.782
of Japanese food.

00:49:15.782 --> 00:49:17.240
A lot of them have
since gone away.

00:49:17.240 --> 00:49:21.450
But what it takes is having a
knowledgeable population there

00:49:21.450 --> 00:49:23.140
that can cook the food.

00:49:23.140 --> 00:49:26.125
I presume that you're
talking about Chicago or--

00:49:26.125 --> 00:49:27.500
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
I'm from Chicago.

00:49:27.500 --> 00:49:28.416
ROBERT SIETSEMA: Yeah.

00:49:28.416 --> 00:49:31.140
Yeah, there were Japanese
people in Chicago that started

00:49:31.140 --> 00:49:33.222
making the food, presumably.

00:49:33.222 --> 00:49:35.430
And then other people learned
how to make it as well.

00:49:35.430 --> 00:49:39.800
But the necessary condition was
to have immigrants from that

00:49:39.800 --> 00:49:40.800
country that were there.

00:49:40.800 --> 00:49:43.490
And that is usually the
case with ethnic food.

00:49:43.490 --> 00:49:47.030
Like I remember when
Mexican food hit Milwaukee.

00:49:47.030 --> 00:49:48.930
It was just unbelievable.

00:49:48.930 --> 00:49:51.390
This un-reconstructed
Mexican food

00:49:51.390 --> 00:49:53.680
from a certain state
in Mexico was suddenly

00:49:53.680 --> 00:49:56.970
available along National
Avenue in Milwaukee.

00:49:56.970 --> 00:49:59.340
And that's happened
all over the country.

00:49:59.340 --> 00:50:01.090
There's been a
revolution whereby

00:50:01.090 --> 00:50:03.780
immigrants going
inland-- maybe they

00:50:03.780 --> 00:50:06.530
lived originally in New
York or Los Angeles--

00:50:06.530 --> 00:50:08.300
and then they started
moving inland.

00:50:08.300 --> 00:50:11.360
Particularly true
of African food.

00:50:11.360 --> 00:50:14.510
Like Nigerian food appeared
in Chicago maybe 20 years ago,

00:50:14.510 --> 00:50:17.430
and was just mind boggling.

00:50:17.430 --> 00:50:20.010
There have to be immigrants
to bring the food,

00:50:20.010 --> 00:50:24.430
or a mass media that transmits
the ideas of the food.

00:50:24.430 --> 00:50:27.780
And now, of course, we
have the-- how is it

00:50:27.780 --> 00:50:29.800
that salsa took
over from ketchup

00:50:29.800 --> 00:50:31.700
as the national condiment?

00:50:31.700 --> 00:50:33.030
That's a story in itself.

00:50:33.030 --> 00:50:35.070
But it required
Mexicans to be here

00:50:35.070 --> 00:50:37.140
and to bring their salsa to us.

00:50:37.140 --> 00:50:40.070
And great chains like
Taco Bell to start

00:50:40.070 --> 00:50:41.937
promoting that condiment.

00:50:41.937 --> 00:50:42.770
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:50:42.770 --> 00:50:45.600
ROBERT SIETSEMA: Sure.

00:50:45.600 --> 00:50:46.225
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:50:46.225 --> 00:50:49.470
So my questions about
burgers-- the obsession

00:50:49.470 --> 00:50:54.090
with burgers in terms of crazier
ingredients and sort of gourmet

00:50:54.090 --> 00:50:56.860
spoke burgers that lots of
restaurants in this city

00:50:56.860 --> 00:51:00.240
and across the country
seems to be unending.

00:51:00.240 --> 00:51:02.890
I wanted to get your
take on that trend,

00:51:02.890 --> 00:51:08.196
and your thoughts on sort of how
we got here, where it's going.

00:51:08.196 --> 00:51:11.640
ROBERT SIETSEMA: Burgers is
an interesting phenomenon,

00:51:11.640 --> 00:51:14.970
because burgers had been with us
since the 1820s when they first

00:51:14.970 --> 00:51:18.640
started appearing on the
lower west side of Manhattan

00:51:18.640 --> 00:51:21.890
to feed German sailors--
without the bun.

00:51:21.890 --> 00:51:23.680
And of course, the
bun first appeared

00:51:23.680 --> 00:51:25.890
any number of
places-- New Haven,

00:51:25.890 --> 00:51:27.720
Connecticut, is one of
the places of claims

00:51:27.720 --> 00:51:30.640
to have invented the
hamburger, which had bread.

00:51:30.640 --> 00:51:33.530
But eventually
hamburgers had buns.

00:51:33.530 --> 00:51:36.280
It's often been known
as comfort food.

00:51:36.280 --> 00:51:38.140
But one of the
things that made them

00:51:38.140 --> 00:51:40.720
so popular in the
current era is what

00:51:40.720 --> 00:51:45.160
I call the glamorization
of plebeian foodstuffs.

00:51:45.160 --> 00:51:48.390
And what that means is
that restaurateurs who

00:51:48.390 --> 00:51:51.320
would formerly serve
you a steak found,

00:51:51.320 --> 00:51:53.510
that by the glamorization
of hamburgers,

00:51:53.510 --> 00:51:56.510
they could give you a hamburger
and you would be just as happy.

00:51:56.510 --> 00:51:58.110
At one time, a
hamburger was something

00:51:58.110 --> 00:52:02.200
that you nibbled at lunch, or
ate at your desk or whatever.

00:52:02.200 --> 00:52:05.160
And now suddenly the
attention we pay hamburgers

00:52:05.160 --> 00:52:08.300
means that instead of
charging $5 apiece for them,

00:52:08.300 --> 00:52:09.680
they can charge $20.

00:52:09.680 --> 00:52:11.360
This is not a bad thing.

00:52:11.360 --> 00:52:13.860
But that same thing has
happened with pizza, whereby

00:52:13.860 --> 00:52:17.320
giant, cheap pizzas shrunk
down to little Neapolitan

00:52:17.320 --> 00:52:20.450
pizzas that were suddenly $18.

00:52:20.450 --> 00:52:25.470
It's one of the ways that cash
strapped restaurateurs who

00:52:25.470 --> 00:52:28.550
occupy this ridiculously
expensive real estate, how

00:52:28.550 --> 00:52:31.320
they're able to make
ends meet by fooling us

00:52:31.320 --> 00:52:34.320
into thinking that we should
pay a lot more for things

00:52:34.320 --> 00:52:35.240
we were accustomed--

00:52:35.240 --> 00:52:37.130
AUDIENCE: So you think
it's economics driven?

00:52:37.130 --> 00:52:38.755
ROBERT SIETSEMA: It's
economics driven,

00:52:38.755 --> 00:52:42.070
but there's no doubt that this
has made every one increase

00:52:42.070 --> 00:52:43.530
their hamburger game.

00:52:43.530 --> 00:52:46.050
And hamburgers are
1,000 times better

00:52:46.050 --> 00:52:49.380
than they were 10
years ago even.

00:52:49.380 --> 00:52:51.530
I love hamburgers and I
eat them all the time,

00:52:51.530 --> 00:52:55.430
but what has happened to
them is just mind boggling.

00:52:55.430 --> 00:52:57.570
They're not the
same thing anymore.

00:52:57.570 --> 00:52:58.300
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:52:58.300 --> 00:53:00.558
ROBERT SIETSEMA: Sure.

